# Component Structure Guidelines

## What goes where
- Reusable components belong in `app/components/`.
- Route-specific components should be co-located near their route (e.g. `app/about/components/...`).

## Exports
- Use **named exports** for components in `app/components/`.
- Avoid `export default` for reusable components.
- Only Next.js route files (`page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`) should use `export default`.

## File naming
- Use `PascalCase.tsx` for components (e.g. `ProjectCard.tsx`, `SectionHeader.tsx`).
- One main component per file.

## TypeScript props
- Define a `Props` type/interface above the component.
- Prefer explicit types; avoid `any`.
- Use `Readonly<>` for props where appropriate.

## Client vs Server
- Do not add `"use client"` unless needed (hooks, event handlers, browser APIs).
- If a component needs `"use client"`, keep it as small as possible and pass data down via props.

## Imports order
1. React/Next imports
2. Third-party libs
3. Local imports (absolute `@/` first, then relative)
4. Styles last (if any)

## Component template
```tsx
import type { ReactNode } from "react";

export type ComponentNameProps = Readonly<{
  title: string;
  children?: ReactNode;
}>;

export function ComponentName({ title, children }: ComponentNameProps) {
  return (
    <section>
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      {children}
    </section>
  );
}
```

## ClassName conventions
- Keep class ordering consistent:
  Layout → Spacing/Sizing → Typography → Colors → Effects → States
- Prefer Tailwind utilities; avoid custom CSS except global tokens/base styles.
